 and others who must read, understand and use research in fields as diverse as health, criminology, education, the environment, transport and housing it provides a one-stop, authoritative guide to making sense of and evaluating the significance of often complex methodologies. The authors are all eminent researchers in the field of health inequalities. They have together produced two glossaries for the Journal of Epidemiology and Community Health and have published a large number of books and articles in learned academic journals.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Feb 2023) 0aEconomicsxSociological aspects. 0aEquality. 7aMEDICAL / Epidemiology.2bisacsh1 aDavey Smith, George, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aGalobardes, Bruna, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aLawlor, Debbie A., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aWheeler, Ben, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBristol University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2013-1995z978311119621340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781447342588423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781447342588/original  a978-3-11-119621-3  Bristol University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2013-1995c1995d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles